}

{
  "solution": "In a bi-elliptic transfer, the second transfer orbit is an elliptical orbit with its apocenter at the distant transfer point (552,476 km) and its pericenter at the final circular orbit radius (138,310 km). The semi-major axis (a) of an ellipse is the average of the pericenter and apocenter distances: a = (r_peri + r_apo) / 2. Here, r_peri = 138,310 km and r_apo = 552,476 km. Thus, a = (138,310 + 552,476) / 2 = 690,786 / 2 = 345,393 km.",
